answers.body_markdown:
Propagating the generic type parameter `OptionType` to consumers of `WithForwardRef` is not directly possible, because TS cannot [propagate  free generic type parameters][1] to consumers (yet!). Simple example:
```
function identity&lt;T&gt;(arg: T) { return arg; }
function memoize&lt;F extends (...args: unknown[]) =&gt; unknown&gt;(fn: F): F { return fn; }
// actual: memid: (arg: unknown) =&gt; unknown
// desired: memid: &lt;T&gt;(arg: T) =&gt; T
// we cannot retain and propagate T to memId here
const memid = memoize(identity);
```
In your case, `export const WithForwardRef = React.forwardRef(...)` returns a concrete Component type, where generic type parameters are already replaced by concrete type instances. The props for the returned component actually have the type `WithForwardRefProps&lt;Option&gt;` now, as `Option` is inferred as compatible type from the constraint `&lt;OptionType extends Option&gt;` (otherwise it would default to `unknown`).

###Solution:
We can remove the generic type parameter `OptionType` and replace it by the base type `Option` inside the given function argument of `React.forwardRef`. Then everything is wrapped in an [additional component][2], which has the `OptionType` type parameter and can properly narrow the type.
```
interface Props&lt;OptionType&gt; {
  onChange: (option: OptionType) =&gt; void;
  options: OptionType[];
}

const WithForwardRef_ = React.forwardRef(
  (props: Props&lt;Option&gt;, ref?: React.Ref&lt;HTMLDivElement&gt;) =&gt; {...}
);

type WithForwardRefProps&lt;OptionType extends Option&gt; = {
  // ref wouldn&#39;t be a valid prop name 
  forwardedRef: React.Ref&lt;HTMLDivElement&gt;;
} &amp; Props&lt;OptionType&gt;;

export const WithForwardRef = &lt;OptionType extends Option&gt;({
  forwardedRef,
  ...rest
}: WithForwardRefProps&lt;OptionType&gt;) =&gt; (
  &lt;WithForwardRef_ {...rest} ref={forwardedRef} /&gt;
);
```
`WithForwardRef` can be used like this:
```
function App() {
  const ref = React.createRef&lt;HTMLDivElement&gt;();
  const options = [
    { label: &quot;foo&quot;, value: 1 },
    { label: &quot;bar&quot;, value: 2 },
    { label: &quot;baz&quot;, value: 3 }
  ];
  return (
    &lt;WithForwardRef
      forwardedRef={ref}
      options={options}
      onChange={o =&gt; console.log(o)} // o has type {label: string; value: number;}
    /&gt;
  );
}
```
[Demo][3]
Hope, it helps!

  [1]: https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/issues/30134
  [2]: https://reactjs.org/docs/forwarding-refs.html#forwarding-refs-in-higher-order-components
  [3]: https://stackblitz.com/edit/so-58469229?file=index.tsx

