Answer 
======

I&#39;m not entirely sure what you are after here but surely the following is what you require

    data = {&quot;A&quot;:&quot;less is more and more is less&quot;}
    temp = {key : (len(sentence.split()), len(set(sentence.split())), sentence) for key, sentence in data.items()}
   
Which returns 

    {&#39;A&#39;: (7, 4, &#39;less is more and more is less&#39;)}

Explanation
===========

We iterate over the dictionary creating a tuple from the initial data comprising of :

 * The total number of words from the count of items in the split sentence
 * The total number of unique words from the count of items in the split sentence re-cast as a set. *In Python a set contains only unique elements.*
 * The original sentence as is.

Update
======

To get a tally of each word in the sentence one can use `groupby` from `itertools`

    from itertools import groupby
    data = {&quot;A&quot;:&quot;less is more and more is less&quot;}
    temp = {key : {word:len(list(items)) for word, items in groupby(sorted(sentence.split()))} for key, sentence in data.items()}

This returns 

    {&#39;A&#39;: {&#39;and&#39;: 1, &#39;is&#39;: 2, &#39;less&#39;: 2, &#39;more&#39;: 2}}

Explanation
===========
Here we use a common Python idiom for counting each `word` in the provided `sentence`.

Groupby 
-------

`groupby` collects sequential items together. The order of the items is quite important and necessarily one must sort the input or manage the output. The string `ABBB` will be grouped into the following structure  

    {
     &quot;A&quot; : (Gobble the &quot;A&quot;&#39;s in string), 
     &quot;B&quot; : (Gobble the &quot;B&quot;&#39;s in string; following &quot;A&quot;)
    }

Python returns the following

    &gt;&gt;&gt; {key : list(val) for key, val in groupby(&quot;ABBB&quot;)}
    {&#39;A&#39;: [&#39;A&#39;], &#39;B&#39;: [&#39;B&#39;, &#39;B&#39;, &#39;B&#39;]}


Comparatively the string `BABB` will be grouped into the fragmented structure 

    {
     &quot;B&quot; : (Gobble the &quot;B&quot;&#39;s in string),                 # This key/value pair gets overridden
     &quot;A&quot; : (Gobble the &quot;A&quot;&#39;s in string; following &quot;B&quot;),
     &quot;B&quot; : (Gobble the &quot;B&quot;&#39;s in string; following &quot;A&quot;)   # This key/value pair supercedes the prior pair
    }

Python returns the following

    &gt;&gt;&gt; {key : list(val) for key, val in groupby(&quot;BABB&quot;)}
    {&#39;B&#39;: [&#39;B&#39;, &#39;B&#39;], &#39;A&#39;: [&#39;A&#39;]}

The latter may be fixed by sorting the data before hand

    &gt;&gt;&gt; {key : list(val) for key, val in groupby(sorted(&quot;BABB&quot;))}
    {&#39;A&#39;: [&#39;A&#39;], &#39;B&#39;: [&#39;B&#39;, &#39;B&#39;, &#39;B&#39;]}

or by managing the resulting key/pair tuples returned 

    &gt;&gt;&gt; data ={}
    &gt;&gt;&gt; for key, val in groupby(&quot;BABB&quot;) :
    ...     data[key] = data.get(key, []) + list(val)
    &gt;&gt;&gt; data
    {&#39;A&#39;: [&#39;A&#39;], &#39;B&#39;: [&#39;B&#39;, &#39;B&#39;, &#39;B&#39;]}

